ne Caplett || \n|-\n|2000 || ''[[Fat Friends]]'' || Mrs. Chadwick || 2 episodes\n|-\n|2000 || ''The Van Boys'' || Mother || Video release\n|-\n|1987 || ''[[Vacuuming Completely Nude in Paradise]]'' || Spaniard || TV movie\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=332246|name=Sandra Gough}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gough, Sandra}}\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Manchester]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{England-tv-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAll Creatures Great and Small(link changed toAll Creatures Great and Small (TV series)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandra_Gough"}
{"title_page": "Rick Fuller", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Rick Fuller\n|image=Rick Fuller 2001.jpg\n|birth_name=Richard Fuller\n|caption= Fuller as the [[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship|Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Champion]].\n|names='''Rick Fuller'''<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/><br />Paul Fuller<ref name=Cage/>\n<!-- Please don't change the height or weight. These are the measures as officially stated and they should not be changed. -->\n|height={{height|ft=6|in=5}}<ref name=Cage/>\n|weight={{convert|286|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=Cage/>\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1967|2|18}}\n|death_date=\n|birth_place=[[Middleboro, Massachusetts]]<ref name=Cage>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.de/?id=2&nr=1106&name=Rick+Fuller|title=Cagematch profile}}</ref>\n|children=2\n|death_place=\n|resides=\n|billed=Middleboro, Massachusetts\n|trainer=[[Jimmy Snuka]]<ref name=OWOW/><br />[[Tony Atlas]]<ref name=OWOW/>\n|debut=1990<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n|retired=\n|website=\n}}\n'''Richard Fuller''' (born February 18, 1967)<ref name=OWOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/r/rick-fuller.html|title=OWOW profile}}</ref><ref name=Cage/> is an American [[professional wrestler]]. He is best known for his appearances as a jobber in [[World Championship Wrestling]]. He would later be featured in several video games including ''[[WCW Nitro (video game)|WCW Nitro]]'' and ''[[WCW/nWo Thunder]]''.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early life and career===\nBorn in [[Middleboro, Massachusetts]], Fuller graduated from [[Middleborough High School]] in 1987 and soon began training under [[Jimmy Snuka|\"Superfly\" Jimmy Snuka]] and [[Tony Atlas|\"Mr. USA\" Tony Atlas]] at their wrestling school in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]].\n\nTouring the Northeast during the 1990s, Fuller won championship titles in several promotions and, most notably, feuded with [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Garland]] while in the New England Wrestling Association later fighting over the NEWA Heavyweight Championship during 1992 and 1993.\n\n===World Championship Wrestling===\nIn early 1997, Fuller made debut in World Championship Wrestling losing to [[Lex Luger]] at the [[Louisiana Superdome|Superdome]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] on January 13, 1997. Regularly appearing on ''[[WCW Monday Nitro]]'', ''[[WCW Saturday Night]]'' during the year, he also lost to [[Chris Benoit]] on February 22<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/ResultsArchive/Wrestlers/benoit.html |title=Wrestling Results Archive: Chris Benoit |author=Nevada, Vance |last2=Baker |first2=Brent |date=2007-06-26 |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref> and [[Diamond Dallas Page]] on March 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/19970303.htm |title=This Week In The WCW: WCW Monday Night Nitro - Monday, 03/03/97 |date= December 1998 |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref> Later that month, he would also face [[Roadblock (wrestler)|Roadblock]] and [[Johnny Swinger]] on ''Saturday Night'' before teaming with Roadblock against Lex Luger and [[The Giant (wrestler)|The Giant]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on March 31, 1997.\n\nSuffering losses to [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] and [[Jeff Jarrett]] during the next two months, he lost to [[Tonga Fifita|Meng]] in a dark match on ''Monday Nitro'' on May 12. After another loss to Jeff Jarrett on ''Saturday Night'' on May 24, he also lost to The Giant in a handicap match with Johnny Swinger and [[Jerry Flynn]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on May 26.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw97.htm |title=WCW: 1997 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131908/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw97.htm |archivedate=2007-12-26 |df= }}</ref> In early June, he would also lose to [[Harold Hoag|Ice Train]] and [[Marcus Bagwell|Buff Bagwell]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehistoryofwcw.com/1997.html |title=World Championship Wrestling: Show Results - 1997 |author=Miguez, Edward C. |year=2004 |publisher=TheHistoryofWCW.com |access-date=2007-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013222908/http://thehistoryofwcw.com/1997.html |archive-date=2007-10-13 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and later to [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] on ''Monday Nitro'' in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on July 13.\n\nOne of the first victims of [[Bill Goldberg]]'s winning streak during early 1998, Fuller was pinned by Goldberg on ''[[WCW Thunder]]'' on February 2. He later appeared on ''[[WCW WorldWide]]'' losing to [[Konnan]] on February 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecubsfan.com/worldwide/1998023w.htm |title=WCW Worldwide - Saturday |date=1998-02-21 |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref> as well as appearing on ''Saturday Night'' facing [[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morris]], Jim Duggan and [[Prince Iaukea]] as well as to Booker T and [[Steve McMichael]] on ''Thunder'' before defeating [[Doc Dean]] on July 25, 1998.\n\nDuring the next few months however, while scoring victories over preliminary wrestlers, he would lose matches to [[Scott Norton]], [[Bryan Clark]], [[Marty Jannetty]] and Jerry Flynn before losing to [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship|WCW World Heavyweight Champion]] Bill Goldberg on ''Thunder'' in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] on September 10. He would also lose to [[Ernest Miller|Ernest \"The Cat\" Miller]] and [[Rick Steiner]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw98.htm |title=WCW: 1998 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131913/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw98.htm |archivedate=2007-12-26 |df= }}</ref> before defeating [[El Dandy]] on ''Worldwide'' on October 17, 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998103w.htm |title=WCW Monday Night Nitro |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref>\n\nFuller defeated [[Lash LeRoux]] on ''WorldWide'' on January 26. Fuller later teamed with [[Knuckles Nelson]] at the NWA Parade of Champions, substituting for the injured Erich Sbraccia, winning the then vacant NWA World Tag Team Championship against Team Extreme (Kit Carson and Khris Germany) winning by reverse decision at the Bronco Bowl in [[Dallas, Texas]] on June 10, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.com/smokyrobmoore/photo1.htm |title=NWA Southwest Bronco Bowl, Dallas, Texas - June 10, 1999 |author=Moore, Rob |date=June 1999 |publisher=Rob Moore, Texas Wrestling Announcer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104105103/http://www.geocities.com/smokyrobmoore/photo1.htm |archivedate=November 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref> However, the two would hold them for less than a week before losing the titles to [[The Public Enemy (professional wrestling)|The Public Enemy]] in [[Bolton, Massachusetts]] on June 17.\n\nFuller would make only occasional appearances with WCW for most of the year, defeating [[Scott Vick|Sick Boy]] on ''Thunder'' in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] on July 14,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw99.htm |title=WCW: 1999 |author=Cawthon, Graham |work=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101144829/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw99.htm |archivedate=2008-01-01 |df= }}</ref> he would instead wrestle  for independent promotions including an appearance at Ultimate Professional Wrestling's Slam & Jam '99 defeating former trainer \"Mr. USA\" Tony Atlas at the [[Augusta Civic Center]] in [[Augusta, Maine]] on December 30, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wen-tv.com/upw/press_releases/pr_Augusta99.htm |title=Slam & Jam '99 Rocks Augusta |date=December 1999 |publisher=Wen-TV.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060523070457/http://www.wen-tv.com/upw/press_releases/pr_Augusta99.htm |archivedate=2006-05-23 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1999/thunder071499 |title=tOa: The Other Arena - Thunder (July 14, 1999) |author=Jacobson, Jeff |year=2002 |publisher=OtherArena.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030610224817/http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1999%2Fthunder071499 |archivedate=June 10, 2003 |df= }}</ref>\n\nReturning to WCW in early 2000, Fuller faced [[Tank Abbott]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on February 14<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rspw.org/petrie/000214.txt |title=Slobberknocker Central Monday Night Recap #222 |author=Petrie, John |date=2000-02-14 |publisher=Rspw.org}}</ref> and later appeared on ''Saturday Night'' during its last months on the air facing [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]], [[Dale Torborg|The Demon]] and in the last episode, participated in a six-man Hardcore Battle Royal won by [[Brian Knobs]] and included [[Norman Smiley]], Adrian Byrd, Dave Burkehead and [[Al Green (wrestler)|The Dog]] on April 1, 2000.\n\n===Return to the independent circuit===\nAfter the close of WCW, Fuller returned to the independent circuit and, while in East Coast Championship Wrestling joined the stable Alliance of Defiance with [[Kevin Kelly (announcer)|Kevin Kelly]] and Billy Fives in early 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerweck.net/jimkettnerinterview.htm |title=Interview: Jim Kettner |author=Gerwick, Steve |date=2001-05-30 |publisher=Gerwick.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204851/http://www.gerweck.net/jimkettnerinterview.htm |archivedate=2007-09-27 |df= }}</ref> He would also make an appearance in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) facing [[Crowbar (wrestler)|Devon Storm]] at the [[Hartford Civic Center]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]] on May 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/01.htm |title=WWF: 2001 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903092034/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/01.htm |archivedate=2004-09-03 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2001, he assaulted then-referee Barry Ace during a match for [[NWA New England]] after he had unintentionally caused Fuller to mistime a wrestling move. NWA New England Vice President Vinnie Capelli later made a public statement accepting full responsibility for the incident as Barry Ace was not a fully trained referee at the time. Despite this incident, Fuller remained with the promotion and, the following year, he won the NWA New England Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1wrestling.com/news/newsline.asp?news=23245 |title=Today In Wrestling History for ... July 13, 2005 |author=Bryan, Jim |date=2005-07-05 |publisher=1wrestling.com }}</ref>  Several years later, Fuller and Ace both portrayed prison inmates in the film ''[[What Doesn't Kill You (film)|What Doesn't Kill You]]''.\n\n===Recent years===\nDuring 2006, Fuller would continue his feud with Brian Milonas in East Coast Championship Wrestling defeating him on May 6 although he was later eliminated by Milonas in the ECCW \"Road to the Championship\" Tournament on May 20. The following month he debuted [[New England Championship Wrestling]] defeating Nat Turner on July 15 although he would later lose to NECW U.S. Champion Eric Shred by disqualification on October 7 and, with Evan Siks, defeated [[Eddie Edwards (wrestler)|Eddie Edwards]] and DC Dillinger by disqualification on October 28, 2006. Defeating Triplelicious and Chris Green during the next several weeks, he joined Team Nightmare (Evan Siks, Jason Blade and Brian Fury) defeating Team Sabotage (Kristian Frost, John Walters, Eddie Edwards and DC Dillinger) in an 8-man elimination match on December 16, 2006.\n\n[[File:Rick Fuller 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Fuller in June 2013.]]\nIn early 2007, he lost to [[Abyss (wrestler)|Abyss]] in a stretcher match during a Powerhouse Wrestling of New England event on January 27 and, the following month in Big Time Wrestling, defeated Eddie Edwards on February 25 before losing to Mister TA in a dog collar match on March 2, 2007. From late 2007 through early 2008, he wrestled for a small company in Fair Haven, Massachusetts called Alliance Championship Wrestling.\n\nOn May 18, 2007 Fuller faced Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Champion Brian Milonas in the main event of the Homecoming benefit show in [[Byfield, Massachusetts]], a fundraising event held by [[Chaotic Wrestling]] and Fabulous Productions to raise money for charities in the New England area including the [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]], the Newbury Police Association and the Trista Zinck Scholarship Fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/cenahomecoming |title=The Champ to make a Homecoming in Massachusetts |author=Medalis, Kara A. |date=2007-05-25 |publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> The match, which featured [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWE World Heavyweight Champion]] [[John Cena]] as special referee, also saw [[Vince McMahon]] in a rare appearance on the independent circuit who attempted to interfere in the match only to be stopped by Cena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/cena.html |title=Bios: John Cena |author=Milner, John |last2=Xamin  |first2=Mark  |date=2005-02-25 |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2007 Fuller defeated Brian Fury to win the [[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]].\n\nOn June 27, 2008, Fuller and tag team partner [[Fred Sampson]] defeated The Blowout Boys to become the new [[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship|Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Champions]].\n\nIn 2008 Fuller competed for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW), where he formed a tag team with [[Matt Bloom|Giant Bernard]]. He is also a singles competitor in the New Jersey-based ISPW and the New England-based Big Time Wrestling (BTW).\n\nRick has also been an extra in many movies and commercials. Including a football player in ''[[The Game Plan (film)|The Game Plan]]'' starring [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] as well as the bouncer in \"The Fighter\".\n\n==Professional wrestling style and persona==\nFuller was frequently known by the nicknames of \"The Lumberjack\" and \"Big\".<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/> His finishing moves included a ''[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver|Fuller Effect]]'' and a [[spinning heel kick]] during his WCW career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otherarena.com/nCo/finish/finish.html|title=Other Arena's Finishing Moves List|publisher=Other Arena|accessdate=2009-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/19970324.htm|title=This Week In The WCW}}</ref> He used a variety of signature moves including a [[Suplex#Belly-to-back suplex|belly to back suplex]],<ref name=Sat>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998023s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on February 14, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big boot|big boot]],<ref name=Sat3>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998041s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on April 5, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling holds#Chinlock|chinlock]],<ref name=Sat/><ref name=Sat2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998032s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on March 7, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Backhand chop|knife-edged chop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1997122s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on December 6, 1997}}</ref>, an [[Backbreaker#Canadian backbreaker rack|overhead gutwrench backbreaker rack]]<ref name=Sat3/> and an [[Professional wrestling attacks#Uppercut|uppercut]].<ref name=Sat2/> Yonosuke Kitamura's \"Dead Label\" was used as his [[music in professional wrestling|theme song]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rmlabel.com/biography.html|title=Biography|last=Kitamura|first=Yonosuke|accessdate=2014-11-14|work=RMLabel|language=Japanese|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127193017/http://rmlabel.com/biography.html|archivedate=2014-11-27|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFuller is married and has two children.<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n[[File:Rick Fuller as TRP Champion.jpg|thumb|Fuller as the TRP Heavyweight Champion in 2007.]]\n*'''[[Chaotic Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/chaotic/chaotic-h.html |title=Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Title |accessdate=|year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n**[[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship]] ([[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Fred Sampson]]\n*'''Eastern Wrestling Alliance'''\n**EWA Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book |author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will |title=Wrestling Title Histories |publisher=Archeus Communications |year=2000|edition=4th |isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''[[NWA New England]]'''\n**NWA New England Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/nehtnwa.html |title=N.W.A. New England Heavyweight Title History |accessdate= |authors=Brian Westcott, Eric Roelfsema and Jim Dupree |year=2007 |publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n**NWA New England Brass Knuckles Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/nwa-newengland/nwa-ne-bk.html |title=N.W.A. New England Brass Knuckles Title |accessdate= |year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323000417/http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/nwa-newengland/nwa-ne-bk.html |archivedate=March 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA Southwest]]'''\n**[[NWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of NWA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Knuckles Nelson]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/nwa/world/nwa-t.html |title=N.W.A. World Tag Team Title |accessdate=|year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n*'''[[New England Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/necw/necw-tc-h.html |title=N.E.C.W. Triple Crown Heavyweight Title |accessdate=2008-01-03 |year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n*'''New England Wrestling Association'''\n**NEWA Heavyweight Championship (4 times)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n**NEWA Interstate Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n**NEWA Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Jack Tanner<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''Powerhouse Wrestling'''\n**PW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Jimmy \"Jact\" Crash<ref>{{cite web |url=http://powerhousene.tripod.com/id35.html |title=Powerhouse Wrestling of New England: \"Big\" Rick Fuller |accessdate= |year=2004 |publisher=Powerhousene.com }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''\n**PWI ranked him #'''189''' of the 500 best singles wrestlers of the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]] in 2009\n*'''Whaling City Wrestling'''\n**WCW Tag Team Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with \"Sweet\" Scott Ashworth<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''[[Top Rope Promotions|Yankee Pro Wrestling / Top Rope Promotions]]'''\n**YPW/TRP Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/r/rick-fuller.html Online World of Wrestling profile]\n*[http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=1106&worker=Rick+Fuller CageMatch profile] {{in lang|de}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090108060047/http://wrestling.xwiki.com/xwiki/bin/view/Main/RickFuller WrestleWiki profile]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0298331|name=Rick Fuller}}\n{{NWA World Tag Team Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fuller, Rick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Middleborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Rick Fuller\n|image=Rick Fuller 2001.jpg\n|birth_name=Richard Fuller\n|caption= Fuller as the [[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship|Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Champion]].\n|names='''Rick Fuller'''<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/><br />Paul Fuller<ref name=Cage/>\n<!-- Please don't change the height or weight. These are the measures as officially stated and they should not be changed. -->\n|height={{height|ft=6|in=5}}<ref name=Cage/>\n|weight={{convert|286|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=Cage/>\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1967|2|18}}\n|death_date=\n|birth_place=[[Middleboro, Massachusetts]]<ref name=Cage>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.de/?id=2&nr=1106&name=Rick+Fuller|title=Cagematch profile}}</ref>\n|children=2\n|death_place=\n|resides=\n|billed=Middleboro, Massachusetts\n|trainer=[[Jimmy Snuka]]<ref name=OWOW/><br />[[Tony Atlas]]<ref name=OWOW/>\n|debut=1990<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n|retired=\n|website=\n}}\n'''Richard Fuller''' (born February 18, 1967)<ref name=OWOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/r/rick-fuller.html|title=OWOW profile}}</ref><ref name=Cage/> is an American [[professional wrestler]]. He is best known for his appearances as a jobber in [[World Championship Wrestling]]. He would later be featured in several video games including ''[[WCW Nitro (video game)|WCW Nitro]]'' and ''[[WCW/nWo Thunder]]''.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early life and career===\nBorn in [[Middleboro, Massachusetts]], Fuller graduated from [[Middleborough High School]] in 1987 and soon began training under [[Jimmy Snuka|\"Superfly\" Jimmy Snuka]] and [[Tony Atlas|\"Mr. USA\" Tony Atlas]] at their wrestling school in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]].\n\nTouring the Northeast during the 1990s, Fuller won championship titles in several promotions and, most notably, feuded with [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Garland]] while in the New England Wrestling Association later fighting over the NEWA Heavyweight Championship during 1992 and 1993.\n\n===World Championship Wrestling===\nIn early 1997, Fuller made debut in World Championship Wrestling losing to [[Lex Luger]] at the [[Louisiana Superdome|Superdome]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] on January 13, 1997. Regularly appearing on ''[[WCW Monday Nitro]]'', ''[[WCW Saturday Night]]'' during the year, he also lost to [[Chris Benoit]] on February 22<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/ResultsArchive/Wrestlers/benoit.html |title=Wrestling Results Archive: Chris Benoit |author=Nevada, Vance |last2=Baker |first2=Brent |date=2007-06-26 |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref> and [[Diamond Dallas Page]] on March 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/19970303.htm |title=This Week In The WCW: WCW Monday Night Nitro - Monday, 03/03/97 |date= December 1998 |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref> Later that month, he would also face [[Roadblock (wrestler)|Roadblock]] and [[Johnny Swinger]] on ''Saturday Night'' before teaming with Roadblock against Lex Luger and [[The Giant (wrestler)|The Giant]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on March 31, 1997.\n\nSuffering losses to [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] and [[Jeff Jarrett]] during the next two months, he lost to [[Tonga Fifita|Meng]] in a dark match on ''Monday Nitro'' on May 12. After another loss to Jeff Jarrett on ''Saturday Night'' on May 24, he also lost to The Giant in a handicap match with Johnny Swinger and [[Jerry Flynn]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on May 26.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw97.htm |title=WCW: 1997 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131908/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw97.htm |archivedate=2007-12-26 |df= }}</ref> In early June, he would also lose to [[Harold Hoag|Ice Train]] and [[Marcus Bagwell|Buff Bagwell]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehistoryofwcw.com/1997.html |title=World Championship Wrestling: Show Results - 1997 |author=Miguez, Edward C. |year=2004 |publisher=TheHistoryofWCW.com |access-date=2007-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013222908/http://thehistoryofwcw.com/1997.html |archive-date=2007-10-13 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and later to [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] on ''Monday Nitro'' in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on July 13.\n\nOne of the first victims of [[Bill Goldberg]]'s winning streak during early 1998, Fuller was pinned by Goldberg on ''[[WCW Thunder]]'' on February 2. He later appeared on ''[[WCW WorldWide]]'' losing to [[Konnan]] on February 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecubsfan.com/worldwide/1998023w.htm |title=WCW Worldwide - Saturday |date=1998-02-21 |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref> as well as appearing on ''Saturday Night'' facing [[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morris]], Jim Duggan and [[Prince Iaukea]] as well as to Booker T and [[Steve McMichael]] on ''Thunder'' before defeating [[Doc Dean]] on July 25, 1998.\n\nDuring the next few months however, while scoring victories over preliminary wrestlers, he would lose matches to [[Scott Norton]], [[Bryan Clark]], [[Marty Jannetty]] and Jerry Flynn before losing to [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship|WCW World Heavyweight Champion]] Bill Goldberg on ''Thunder'' in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] on September 10. He would also lose to [[Ernest Miller|Ernest \"The Cat\" Miller]] and [[Rick Steiner]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw98.htm |title=WCW: 1998 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226131913/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw98.htm |archivedate=2007-12-26 |df= }}</ref> before defeating [[El Dandy]] on ''Worldwide'' on October 17, 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998103w.htm |title=WCW Monday Night Nitro |publisher=DDTdigest.com}}</ref>\n\nFuller defeated [[Lash LeRoux]] on ''WorldWide'' on January 26. Fuller later teamed with [[Knuckles Nelson]] at the NWA Parade of Champions, substituting for the injured Erich Sbraccia, winning the then vacant NWA World Tag Team Championship against Team Extreme (Kit Carson and Khris Germany) winning by reverse decision at the Bronco Bowl in [[Dallas, Texas]] on June 10, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.com/smokyrobmoore/photo1.htm |title=NWA Southwest Bronco Bowl, Dallas, Texas - June 10, 1999 |author=Moore, Rob |date=June 1999 |publisher=Rob Moore, Texas Wrestling Announcer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104105103/http://www.geocities.com/smokyrobmoore/photo1.htm |archivedate=November 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref> However, the two would hold them for less than a week before losing the titles to [[The Public Enemy (professional wrestling)|The Public Enemy]] in [[Bolton, Massachusetts]] on June 17.\n\nFuller would make only occasional appearances with WCW for most of the year, defeating [[Scott Vick|Sick Boy]] on ''Thunder'' in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] on July 14,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw99.htm |title=WCW: 1999 |author=Cawthon, Graham |work=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101144829/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/wcw99.htm |archivedate=2008-01-01 |df= }}</ref> he would instead wrestle  for independent promotions including an appearance at Ultimate Professional Wrestling's Slam & Jam '99 defeating former trainer \"Mr. USA\" Tony Atlas at the [[Augusta Civic Center]] in [[Augusta, Maine]] on December 30, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wen-tv.com/upw/press_releases/pr_Augusta99.htm |title=Slam & Jam '99 Rocks Augusta |date=December 1999 |publisher=Wen-TV.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060523070457/http://www.wen-tv.com/upw/press_releases/pr_Augusta99.htm |archivedate=2006-05-23 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1999/thunder071499 |title=tOa: The Other Arena - Thunder (July 14, 1999) |author=Jacobson, Jeff |year=2002 |publisher=OtherArena.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030610224817/http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1999%2Fthunder071499 |archivedate=June 10, 2003 |df= }}</ref>\n\nReturning to WCW in early 2000, Fuller faced [[Tank Abbott]] on ''Monday Nitro'' on February 14<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rspw.org/petrie/000214.txt |title=Slobberknocker Central Monday Night Recap #222 |author=Petrie, John |date=2000-02-14 |publisher=Rspw.org}}</ref> and later appeared on ''Saturday Night'' during its last months on the air facing [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]], [[Dale Torborg|The Demon]] and in the last episode, participated in a six-man Hardcore Battle Royal won by [[Brian Knobs]] and included [[Norman Smiley]], Adrian Byrd, Dave Burkehead and [[Al Green (wrestler)|The Dog]] on April 1, 2000.\n\n===Return to the independent circuit===\nAfter the close of WCW, Fuller returned to the independent circuit and, while in East Coast Championship Wrestling joined the stable Alliance of Defiance with [[Kevin Kelly (announcer)|Kevin Kelly]] and Billy Fives in early 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gerweck.net/jimkettnerinterview.htm |title=Interview: Jim Kettner |author=Gerwick, Steve |date=2001-05-30 |publisher=Gerwick.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204851/http://www.gerweck.net/jimkettnerinterview.htm |archivedate=2007-09-27 |df= }}</ref> He would also make an appearance in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) facing [[Crowbar (wrestler)|Devon Storm]] at the [[Hartford Civic Center]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]] on May 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/01.htm |title=WWF: 2001 |author=Cawthon, Graham |publisher=The History of the WWE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903092034/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/01.htm |archivedate=2004-09-03 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2001, he assaulted then-referee Barry Ace during a match for [[NWA New England]] after he had unintentionally caused Fuller to mistime a wrestling move. NWA New England Vice President Vinnie Capelli later made a public statement accepting full responsibility for the incident as Barry Ace was not a fully trained referee at the time. Despite this incident, Fuller remained with the promotion and, the following year, he won the NWA New England Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1wrestling.com/news/newsline.asp?news=23245 |title=Today In Wrestling History for ... July 13, 2005 |author=Bryan, Jim |date=2005-07-05 |publisher=1wrestling.com }}</ref>  Several years later, Fuller and Ace both portrayed prison inmates in the film ''[[What Doesn't Kill You (film)|What Doesn't Kill You]]''.\n\n===Recent years===\nDuring 2006, Fuller would continue his feud with Brian Milonas in East Coast Championship Wrestling defeating him on May 6 although he was later eliminated by Milonas in the ECCW \"Road to the Championship\" Tournament on May 20. The following month he debuted [[New England Championship Wrestling]] defeating Nat Turner on July 15 although he would later lose to NECW U.S. Champion Eric Shred by disqualification on October 7 and, with Evan Siks, defeated [[Eddie Edwards (wrestler)|Eddie Edwards]] and DC Dillinger by disqualification on October 28, 2006. Defeating Triplelicious and Chris Green during the next several weeks, he joined Team Nightmare (Evan Siks, Jason Blade and Brian Fury) defeating Team Sabotage (Kristian Frost, John Walters, Eddie Edwards and DC Dillinger) in an 8-man elimination match on December 16, 2006.\n\n[[File:Rick Fuller 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Fuller in June 2013.]]\nIn early 2007, he lost to [[Abyss (wrestler)|Abyss]] in a stretcher match during a Powerhouse Wrestling of New England event on January 27 and, the following month in Big Time Wrestling, defeated Eddie Edwards on February 25 before losing to Mister TA in a dog collar match on March 2, 2007. From late 2007 through early 2008, he wrestled for a small company in Fair Haven, Massachusetts called Alliance Championship Wrestling.\n\nOn May 18, 2007 Fuller faced Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Champion Brian Milonas in the main event of the Homecoming benefit show in [[Byfield, Massachusetts]], a fundraising event held by [[Chaotic Wrestling]] and Fabulous Productions to raise money for charities in the New England area including the [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]], the Newbury Police Association and the Trista Zinck Scholarship Fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/cenahomecoming |title=The Champ to make a Homecoming in Massachusetts |author=Medalis, Kara A. |date=2007-05-25 |publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> The match, which featured [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWE World Heavyweight Champion]] [[John Cena]] as special referee, also saw [[Vince McMahon]] in a rare appearance on the independent circuit who attempted to interfere in the match only to be stopped by Cena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/cena.html |title=Bios: John Cena |author=Milner, John |last2=Xamin  |first2=Mark  |date=2005-02-25 |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2007 Fuller defeated Brian Fury to win the [[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]].\n\nOn June 27, 2008, Fuller and tag team partner [[Fred Sampson]] defeated The Blowout Boys to become the new [[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship|Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Champions]].\n\nIn 2008 Fuller competed for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW), where he formed a tag team with [[Matt Bloom|Giant Bernard]]. He is also a singles competitor in the New Jersey-based ISPW and the New England-based Big Time Wrestling (BTW).\n\nRick has also been an extra in many movies and commercials. Including a football player in ''[[The Game Plan (film)|The Game Plan]]'' starring [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] as well as the bouncer in \"The Fighter\".\n\n==Professional wrestling style and persona==\nFuller was frequently known by the nicknames of \"The Lumberjack\" and \"Big\".<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/> His finishing moves included a ''[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver|Fuller Effect]]'' and a [[spinning heel kick]] during his WCW career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otherarena.com/nCo/finish/finish.html|title=Other Arena's Finishing Moves List|publisher=Other Arena|accessdate=2009-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/19970324.htm|title=This Week In The WCW}}</ref> He used a variety of signature moves including a [[Suplex#Belly-to-back suplex|belly to back suplex]],<ref name=Sat>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998023s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on February 14, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big boot|big boot]],<ref name=Sat3>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998041s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on April 5, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling holds#Chinlock|chinlock]],<ref name=Sat/><ref name=Sat2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998032s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on March 7, 1998}}</ref> a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Backhand chop|knife-edged chop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1997122s.htm|title=Saturday Night report on December 6, 1997}}</ref>, an [[Backbreaker#Canadian backbreaker rack|overhead gutwrench backbreaker rack]]<ref name=Sat3/> and an [[Professional wrestling attacks#Uppercut|uppercut]].<ref name=Sat2/> Yonosuke Kitamura's \"Dead Label\" was used as his [[music in professional wrestling|theme song]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rmlabel.com/biography.html|title=Biography|last=Kitamura|first=Yonosuke|accessdate=2014-11-14|work=RMLabel|language=Japanese|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127193017/http://rmlabel.com/biography.html|archivedate=2014-11-27|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFuller is married and has two children.<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n[[File:Rick Fuller as TRP Champion.jpg|thumb|Fuller as the TRP Heavyweight Champion in 2007.]]\n*'''[[Chaotic Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/chaotic/chaotic-h.html |title=Chaotic Wrestling Heavyweight Title |accessdate=|year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n**[[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship]] ([[Chaotic Wrestling Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Fred Sampson]]\n*'''Eastern Wrestling Alliance'''\n**EWA Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book |author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will |title=Wrestling Title Histories |publisher=Archeus Communications |year=2000|edition=4th |isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''[[NWA New England]]'''\n**NWA New England Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/nehtnwa.html |title=N.W.A. New England Heavyweight Title History |accessdate= |authors=Brian Westcott, Eric Roelfsema and Jim Dupree |year=2007 |publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n**NWA New England Brass Knuckles Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/nwa-newengland/nwa-ne-bk.html |title=N.W.A. New England Brass Knuckles Title |accessdate= |year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323000417/http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/nwa-newengland/nwa-ne-bk.html |archivedate=March 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Alliance|NWA Southwest]]'''\n**[[NWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of NWA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Knuckles Nelson]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/nwa/world/nwa-t.html |title=N.W.A. World Tag Team Title |accessdate=|year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n*'''[[New England Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NECW Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/necw/necw-tc-h.html |title=N.E.C.W. Triple Crown Heavyweight Title |accessdate=2008-01-03 |year=2003 |publisher=Puroreso Dojo}}</ref>\n*'''New England Wrestling Association'''\n**NEWA Heavyweight Championship (4 times)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n**NEWA Interstate Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n**NEWA Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Jack Tanner<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''Powerhouse Wrestling'''\n**PW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Jimmy \"Jact\" Crash<ref>{{cite web |url=http://powerhousene.tripod.com/id35.html |title=Powerhouse Wrestling of New England: \"Big\" Rick Fuller |accessdate= |year=2004 |publisher=Powerhousene.com }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''\n**PWI ranked him #'''189''' of the 500 best singles wrestlers of the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]] in 2009\n*'''Whaling City Wrestling'''\n**WCW Tag Team Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with \"Sweet\" Scott Ashworth<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''[[Top Rope Promotions|Yankee Pro Wrestling / Top Rope Promotions]]'''\n**YPW/TRP Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/r/rick-fuller.html Online World of Wrestling profile]\n*[http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=1106&worker=Rick+Fuller CageMatch profile] {{in lang|de}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090108060047/http://wrestling.xwiki.com/xwiki/bin/view/Main/RickFuller WrestleWiki profile]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0298331|name=Rick Fuller}}\n{{NWA World Tag Team Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fuller, Rick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Middleborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed unsupported cite parameter deadurl to url-status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Fuller"}
