| stadium = Devonport Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = Hill\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 22 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 6-0\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ponsonby V Otahuhu\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16289\n| date = 1916-07-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160724.2.61.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>| away = Otahuhu\n| try1 = S Jones, D Norgrove\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance =\n| referee = Clow\n}}\n\n==Roope Rooster Knockout Competition==\nThere were 3,000 spectators in attendance at the Round 1 matches at Victoria Park.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Fight for the Silver Cock/Ponsonby Takes Revenge/Merited Win From Shore/Newton Win and Grafton Default\n| page =6\n| work = Auckland Star |volume=XLVII |issue=181\n| date = 1916-09-30\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19160731.2.57\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> There were 3,000 in attendance again for the semi final between [[City Rovers]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], again played at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] in muddy conditions. As the result was a draw it meant that the teams and [[Auckland Rugby League]] had to decide on how to proceed with the competition. The eventual decision was for [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] to advance to the final and [[City Rovers]] to play [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] in a second semi final. [[City Rovers|City]] defeated [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] and then in the final they defeated [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] in front of almost 5,000 spectators.\n\n===Round 1===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 29 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 8-2\n| report = <ref name=\"roopes_rooster\">{{cite news\n| title =Roope\u2019s Rooster/Ponsonby V North Shore/Newton Defeats Otahuhu\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16295\n| date = 1916-07-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160731.2.77.1| accessdate = 2019-08-12}}</ref>\n| away = North Shore\n| try1 = L Martin 2\n| con1 = J Winters\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = Jack Paul (one mark)\n| stadium = Victoria 1\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = Murray\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 29 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 22-8\n| report = <ref name=\"roopes_rooster\" />\n| away = Otahuhu\n| try1 = [[George Iles]] 2, Thomas 2, Joe Bennett, R Lovett\n| con1 = Coates, Potier\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Spinley, Stanaway\n| con2 = Stanaway\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 2\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = Whitley\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 29 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = WBD-LBD\n| report = <ref name=\"roopes_rooster\" />| away = Grafton\n| try1 =\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 3\n| attendance =\n| referee = Fielding\n}}\n\n===Semi Final===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 5 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 5-5\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope\u2019s Rooster/City V Ponsonby\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16301\n| date = 1916-08-07\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160807.2.118.1| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = J Sutton\n| con1 =\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| try2 = [[Thomas McClymont]]\n| con2 = A Cross\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = Herrick\n}}\n \n===Semi Final===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 12 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 16-3\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Match/City Defeats Newton\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16037\n| date = 1916-08-14\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160814.2.94.1| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n| away = Newton\n| try1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Jim Rukutai]], Harry Francis, J Sutton\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| pen1 =\n| drop1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| try2 = Arthur Isles\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 1\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = A Ferguson\n}}\n\n===Final===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 19 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 11-5\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Won by City Rovers/City Defeats Ponsonby\n| page =3\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16313\n| date = 1916-09-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160821.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-13}}</ref>\n| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = R Clarke, [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], H Lunn\n| con1 =\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| try2 = [[Thomas McClymont]]\n| con2 = A Cross\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 5000\n| referee = T Fielding\n}}\n\n==Top Try Scorers and Point Scorers==\nThe following point scoring lists include both Senior Championship matches and the Roope Rooster competition. [[Karl Ifwersen]] was the top point scorer for the third consecutive year with 58 points. He also topped the try scoring list with 8.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries\n|-\n|1||[[Karl Ifwersen]]||Grafton Athletic||8\n|-\n|2||Nicholson||North Shore||7\n|-\n|2||[[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]||North Shore||7\n|-\n|2||[[George Iles]]||Newton Rangers||7\n|-\n|5||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||5\n|-\n|5||Perrett||North Shore||5\n|-\n|7||T Paul||North Shore||4\n|-\n|7||J Sutton||City Rovers||4\n|-\n|7||[[Jim Rukutai]]||City Rovers||4\n|-\n|7||[[Thomas McClymont]]||Ponsonby United||4\n|-\n|7||L Martin||Ponsonby United||4\n|-\n|7||D Norgrove||Ponsonby United||4\n|-\n|7||[[Dougie McGregor]]||Grafton Athletic||4\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Mark!!DG!!Points\n|-\n|1||[[Karl Ifwersen]]||Grafton Athletic||8||6||10||0||0||56\n|-\n|2||Jack Paul||North Shore||1||14||7||2||0||49\n|-\n|3||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||5||2||3||1||2||31\n|-\n|4||[[George Iles]]||Newton Rangers||7||1||0||0||0||23\n|-\n|5||[[Ernie Asher]]||City Rovers||0||6||5||0||0||22\n|-\n|6||Nicholson||North Shore||7||0||0||0||0||21\n|-\n|6||[[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]||North Shore||7||0||0||0||0||21\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Lower Grade Clubs==\nThe Telegraph Messengers Club nominated a team for the Sixth Grade. They were usually named Post and Telegraph in the media reports during the season.\n*[[Manukau Magpies|Manukau]]\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote Ramblers]]\n*[[Post and Telegraph]]\n*[[Richmond Rovers|Richmond]]\n*Riverhead\n*Sunnyside\n*[[Thames Old Boys]]\n\n==End of Season Exhibition Matches==\nThe week after the final was played [[City Rovers]] travelled to [[Ngaruawahia]] to play Lower Waikato. City won by 13 points to 9. A week later [[Richmond Rovers|Richmond]] and Thames Old Boys (based in Auckland) traveled to [[Thames]] to play a match. It was won by Thames Old Boys by 11 to 5.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Excursion to Thames/Richmond V Old Boys\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16325\n| date = 1916-09-04\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160904.2.115.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\nThe last match of the season was played on the 9th of September when [[City Rovers]] played against Lower Waikato at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]]. [[City Rovers]] won by 19 points to 8. This brought the [[Auckland Rugby League]] season to a close. The curtain-raiser was a match between the Referees Association and Auckland rugby league players and was won by the referees by 10 points to 5.<ref>{{cite news \n| title = Waikato v City Rovers/The Season Closed\n| page =10\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16331\n| date = 1916-09-11\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160911.2.117.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==Representative Fixtures==\nThere were no representative fixtures played in 1916 owing to the effects of the war on senior playing numbers.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]] \n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1916_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Eric Thorne", "text_new": "[[File:Eric Thorne in The Merry Widow.jpg|thumb|140px|Thorne in ''The Merry Widow'']]\n'''Eric Thorne''' (1862\u20131922) was an English singer and actor in [[musical theatre]] and [[comic opera]]. He only rarely used his formal name of '''Frederick Thomas Thorne'''.\n\n==Life==\nIn February 1884, Thorne joined the chorus of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company|D'Oyly Carte]]\u2019s touring \"A\" Company.<ref name=carte>[https://gsarchive.net/whowaswho/T/ThorneEric.htm Eric Thorne] at gsarchive.net/whowaswho, accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Later that year, the tour arrived at [[Portsea, Portsmouth#Portsea|Portsea]], and while they were there Thorne married another member of the company, Ada Dor\u00e9e, whose name was previously Ada Ear\u00e9e.<ref>\u201dThorne Eric & Earee Ada Catherine E\u201d in Marriages for Portsea, vol 2b (1884), p. 840</ref> Her father, William Ear\u00e9e, was a [[Church of England]] [[clergy]]man, and the  [[Banns]] were published three times in July in the names of Frederick Thomas Thorne \u201cof this parish\u201d, and Ada Catherine Elizabeth Ear\u00e9e, of [[Alphamstone]].<ref>\u201cBanns Published 13th, 20th, and 27th July 1884\u201d in Banns book of Portsea Island, p. 214, at www.ancestry.co.uk {{subscription}}</ref> Her father was the Rector there, and her brother [[Robert Brisco Ear\u00e9e]] was also a clergyman.\n\nAda had been born in [[Cockermouth]], [[Cumberland]], in 1850, and specialized in [[operetta]], with a focus on [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]. She had many stage credits between the 1870s and the 1890s.<ref name=eliehistory>[http://www.eliehistory.com/explore/earlsferry-house-part-2/ POTTED HISTORY No 2: Earlsferry House \u2013 Part 2 \u2013 The Glovers] at eliehistory.com</ref> The couple\u2019s daughter Gladys was born at Alphamstone on 17 June 1885<ref name=gladys>\u201dDOREE-THORNE GLADYS EDITH H 17JE1885\u201d in Deaths for Worthing, vol. 18 (1979), p. 2,496</ref> and christened there on 31 August as Gladys Edith Hilda Ear\u00e9e Thorne. Her parents\u2019 names were stated as Frederic Thorne and Ada Catherine Elizabeth Thorne.<ref>\u201cGladys Edith Hilda Earee Thorne\u201d in the Church of England Births and Baptisms, 1813-1918, Alphamstone St Barnabas, Essex, at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 9 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\t\n\nIn March 1885, Thorne briefly took the place of Walter Greyling as King Hildebrand in ''[[Princess Ida]]'', and in May he took over from Hugh Seton as Sir Marmaduke Pointdextre in ''[[The Sorcerer]]'' and as Florian in ''Princess Ida''. In June 1885, ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' was added to the company\u2019s repertoire, and Thorne was given the part of Dick Deadeye. However, the couple\u2019s time with the D'Oyly Carte came to an end in December 1885, when Company \"A\" was closed down.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn the spring of 1888, Thorne sang the part of the Lord Chamberlain in a touring production of ''The Punch Bowl'', a musical comedy about a prince who believes he is invisible.<ref>[[Kurt G\u00e4nzl]], ''The British musical theatre'', Vol. 1 (Macmillan, 1986), p. 349</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 1889, Thorne opened at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in the comic opera ''[[Faddimir]]'', singing the lead part of Faddimir the First,<ref>\u201cFaddimir, or the Triumph of Orthodoxy\u201d in ''The Theatre'', Volume 22 (Wyman & Sons, 1889), p. 335</ref> with his wife also in the company.<ref name=carte/>\n\nThorne made a name for himself in light opera and musical comedy in the West End, the provinces, and overseas, and toured France, Holland, Germany, Belgium, and the United States. He sang the part of Hilarius, the doll maker, in ''[[La poup\u00e9e|La Poup\u00e9e]]'' in a long run which lasted for several years. He had leading parts in ''[[The Lady Dandies]]'', ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', ''[[Les p'tites Michu|The Little Michus]]'', ''[[The Dollar Princess]]'', and ''[[The Waltz Dream]]''.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn 1904, Ada Dor\u00e9e was left an [[annuity]], and a pony and trap, in the will of Thomas Craigie Glover, of Edinburgh, to thank her for looking after him following the death of his wife in 1895.<ref name=eliehistory/>\n\nIn 1911, Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne made the Census return for 4, Wharfedale Street, [[Earl\u2019s Court]], stating herself as head of the household, living on a \u201csmall annuity\u201d. With her were her daughter Gladys Dor\u00e9e-Thorne, single, aged 25, born at Alphamstone Rectory, Essex, a visitor, and a servant.<ref>Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne, [[1911 United Kingdom census]] return for 4, Wharfedale Street, Earl\u2019s Court S.W., at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 9 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912, Thorne sang the part of Grand Duke Rutzinov in a production of [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[The Count of Luxembourg]]'',<ref>[http://www.operascotland.org/tour/2726/Count-of-Luxembourg-1912 The Count of Luxembourg (1912)] at operascotland.org; W. J. MacQueen-Pope, ''Shirtfronts and sables: a story of the days when money could be spent'' (Hale, 1953), p. 59</ref> as one of the five principals, together with [[Daisy Burrell]], [[Lauri de Frece]], [[Robert Michaelis]], and Phyllis le Grand, who were collectively described by the ''Musical News'' as \"all consummate artists in their own style\".<ref>''Musical News and Herald'', vol. 42 (1912), p. 194</ref>\n\nBetween January and March 1914, Thorne sang in [[P. G. Wodehouse]]\u2019s ''[[Nuts and Wine]]'' at the [[Empire, Leicester Square|Empire Theatre, Leicester Square]].<ref>[http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/London%20Revues%201910-1914.pdf London Reviews 1910\u20131914 Over the Footlights], p. 14, at overthefootlights.co.uk, accessed 9 April 2020</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 1916, Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne died at St Saviour's Hospital, [[St Pancras, London]], aged 66,<ref name=eliehistory/><ref>\u201cThorne Ada C E, 66\u201d in Deaths for Pancras, vol. 1b (1916), p. 9</ref> leaving an estate valued at \u00a31,589, with her daughter as Executor.<ref>\u201dDOREE-THORNE Ada otherwise THORNE (wife of Eric Thorne)\u201d in Probate Index for England and Wales, 1916</ref> The death of Thorne followed in 1922.<ref name=carte/> Their daughter Gladys, of 10, Weston Place, Worthing, died on 22 December 1979, aged 94, and probate was granted the next year in the amount of \u00a34,860, in the name of Gladys Edith Hilda Earee Doree-Thorne.<ref name=gladys/><ref>\u201d DOREE-THORNE, Gladys Edith Hilda Earee\u201d in Probate Index for England and Wales, 1980</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp97993/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at National Portrait Gallery\n*[https://theatricalia.com/person/cq9/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at theatricalia.com\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thorne, Eric}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Eric Thorne in The Merry Widow.jpg|thumb|140px|Thorne in ''The Merry Widow'']]\n'''Eric Thorne''' (1862\u20131922) was an English singer and actor in [[musical theatre]] and [[comic opera]]. He only rarely used his formal name of '''Frederick Thomas Thorne'''.\n\n==Life==\nIn February 1884, Thorne joined the chorus of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company|D'Oyly Carte]]\u2019s touring \"A\" Company.<ref name=carte>[https://gsarchive.net/whowaswho/T/ThorneEric.htm Eric Thorne] at gsarchive.net/whowaswho, accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Later that year, the tour arrived at [[Portsea, Portsmouth#Portsea|Portsea]], and while they were there Thorne married another member of the company, Ada Dor\u00e9e, whose name was previously Ada Ear\u00e9e.<ref>\u201dThorne Eric & Earee Ada Catherine E\u201d in Marriages for Portsea, vol 2b (1884), p. 840</ref> Her father, William Ear\u00e9e, was a [[Church of England]] [[clergy]]man, and the  [[Banns]] were published three times in July in the names of Frederick Thomas Thorne \u201cof this parish\u201d, and Ada Catherine Elizabeth Ear\u00e9e, of [[Alphamstone]].<ref>\u201cBanns Published 13th, 20th, and 27th July 1884\u201d in Banns book of Portsea Island, p. 214, at www.ancestry.co.uk {{subscription}}</ref> Her father was the Rector there, and her brother [[Robert Brisco Ear\u00e9e]] was also a clergyman.\n\nAda had been born in [[Cockermouth]], [[Cumberland]], in 1850, and specialized in [[operetta]], with a focus on [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]. She had many stage credits between the 1870s and the 1890s.<ref name=eliehistory>[http://www.eliehistory.com/explore/earlsferry-house-part-2/ POTTED HISTORY No 2: Earlsferry House \u2013 Part 2 \u2013 The Glovers] at eliehistory.com</ref> The couple\u2019s daughter Gladys was born at Alphamstone on 17 June 1885<ref name=gladys>\u201dDOREE-THORNE GLADYS EDITH H 17JE1885\u201d in Deaths for Worthing, vol. 18 (1979), p. 2,496</ref> and christened there on 31 August as Gladys Edith Hilda Ear\u00e9e Thorne. Her parents\u2019 names were stated as Frederic Thorne and Ada Catherine Elizabeth Thorne.<ref>\u201cGladys Edith Hilda Earee Thorne\u201d in the Church of England Births and Baptisms, 1813-1918, Alphamstone St Barnabas, Essex, at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 9 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\t\n\nIn March 1885, Thorne briefly took the place of Walter Greyling as King Hildebrand in ''[[Princess Ida]]'', and in May he took over from Hugh Seton as Sir Marmaduke Pointdextre in ''[[The Sorcerer]]'' and as Florian in ''Princess Ida''. In June 1885, ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' was added to the company\u2019s repertoire, and Thorne was given the part of Dick Deadeye. However, the couple\u2019s time with the D'Oyly Carte came to an end in December 1885, when Company \"A\" was closed down.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn the spring of 1888, Thorne sang the part of the Lord Chamberlain in a touring production of ''The Punch Bowl'', a musical comedy about a prince who believes he is invisible.<ref>[[Kurt G\u00e4nzl]], ''The British musical theatre'', Vol. 1 (Macmillan, 1986), p. 349</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 1889, Thorne opened at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in the comic opera ''[[Faddimir]]'', singing the lead part of Faddimir the First,<ref>\u201cFaddimir, or the Triumph of Orthodoxy\u201d in ''The Theatre'', Volume 22 (Wyman & Sons, 1889), p. 335</ref> with his wife also in the company.<ref name=carte/>\n\nThorne made a name for himself in light opera and musical comedy in the West End, the provinces, and overseas, and toured France, Holland, Germany, Belgium, and the United States. He sang the part of Hilarius, the doll maker, in ''[[La poup\u00e9e|La Poup\u00e9e]]'' in a long run which lasted for several years. He had leading parts in ''[[The Lady Dandies]]'', ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', ''[[Les p'tites Michu|The Little Michus]]'', ''[[The Dollar Princess]]'', and ''[[The Waltz Dream]]''.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn 1904, Ada Dor\u00e9e was left an [[annuity]], and a pony and trap, in the will of Thomas Craigie Glover, of Edinburgh, to thank her for looking after him following the death of his wife in 1895.<ref name=eliehistory/>\n\nIn 1911, Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne made the Census return for 4, Wharfedale Street, [[Earl\u2019s Court]], stating herself as head of the household, living on a \u201csmall annuity\u201d. With her were her daughter Gladys Dor\u00e9e-Thorne, single, aged 25, born at Alphamstone Rectory, Essex, a visitor, and a servant.<ref>Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne, [[1911 United Kingdom census]] return for 4, Wharfedale Street, Earl\u2019s Court S.W., at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 9 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912, Thorne sang the part of Grand Duke Rutzinov in a production of [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[The Count of Luxembourg]]'',<ref>[http://www.operascotland.org/tour/2726/Count-of-Luxembourg-1912 The Count of Luxembourg (1912)] at operascotland.org; W. J. MacQueen-Pope, ''Shirtfronts and sables: a story of the days when money could be spent'' (Hale, 1953), p. 59</ref> as one of the five principals, together with [[Daisy Burrell]], [[Lauri de Frece]], [[Robert Michaelis]], and Phyllis le Grand, who were collectively described by the ''Musical News'' as \"all consummate artists in their own style\".<ref>''Musical News and Herald'', vol. 42 (1912), p. 194</ref>\n\nBetween January and March 1914, Thorne sang in [[P. G. Wodehouse]]\u2019s ''[[Nuts and Wine]]'' at the [[Empire, Leicester Square|Empire Theatre, Leicester Square]].\n\nOn 28 April 1916, Ada Dor\u00e9e-Thorne died at St Saviour's Hospital, [[St Pancras, London]], aged 66,<ref name=eliehistory/><ref>\u201cThorne Ada C E, 66\u201d in Deaths for Pancras, vol. 1b (1916), p. 9</ref> leaving an estate valued at \u00a31,589, with her daughter as Executor.<ref>\u201dDOREE-THORNE Ada otherwise THORNE (wife of Eric Thorne)\u201d in Probate Index for England and Wales, 1916</ref> The death of Thorne followed in 1922.<ref name=carte/> Their daughter Gladys, of 10, Weston Place, Worthing, died on 22 December 1979, aged 94, and probate was granted the next year in the amount of \u00a34,860, in the name of Gladys Edith Hilda Earee Doree-Thorne.<ref name=gladys/><ref>\u201d DOREE-THORNE, Gladys Edith Hilda Earee\u201d in Probate Index for England and Wales, 1980</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp97993/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at National Portrait Gallery\n*[https://theatricalia.com/person/cq9/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at theatricalia.com\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thorne, Eric}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Thorne"}
{"title_page": "Ida Schuster", "text_new": "{{Notability|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =  Ida Schuster\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1918|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|4|9|1918|9|28}}\n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Actress\n| yearsactive = 1937\u20132007\n}}\n\n'''Ida Schuster''' (28 September 1918 \u2013 9 April 2020) was a Scottish actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/citizenstheatre/status/1045591518512394240|title=Citizens Theatre on Twitter|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nOne of nine children, her parents were Jewish immigrants who moved from [[Wilno|Wilno, Poland]] (now [[Vilnius|Vilnius, Lithuania]] to Glasgow at the end of the 19th century. Her older sister, Ray, married [https://universityofglasgowlibrary.wordpress.com/2017/07/06/avrom-greenbaum-and-the-glasgow-jewish-institute-players-draft/ Avrom Greenbaum], who founded the [[Glasgow Jewish Institute Players]] (GJIP),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12590021.Forever_young_and_maternally_yours|title=Forever young and maternally yours|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref> and her brother, Leon Schuster, was production manager for GJIP, and, later, [[Glasgow Unity Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/portal/files/149374061/From_the_Gorbals_to_the_Lower_East_Side_the_theatrical_and_social_cosmopolitanism_of_the_Glasgow_Jewish_Institute_Players.pdf|title=Biography|website=pure.qub.ac.uk|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIda married doctor, Allan Berkeley, until his death in 1990, after 45 years of marriage. At the time of his death, she was appearing in ''The Steamie'' and had to leave the cast. The couple had two children, Howard and Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/evening-times/20060922/281951718302046|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=pressreader.com|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> She lived in Glasgow.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[La mort en direct]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[A Shot at Glory]]'' (2000)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0776843}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schuster, Ida}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish centenarians]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jews]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =  Ida Schuster\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1918|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|2020|4|9|1918|9|28}}\n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Actress\n| yearsactive = 1937\u20132007\n}}\n\n'''Ida Schuster''' (28 September 1918 \u2013 9 April 2020) was a Scottish actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/citizenstheatre/status/1045591518512394240|title=Citizens Theatre on Twitter|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nOne of nine children, her parents were Jewish immigrants who moved from [[Wilno|Wilno, Poland]] (now [[Vilnius|Vilnius, Lithuania]] to Glasgow at the end of the 19th century. Her older sister, Ray, married [https://universityofglasgowlibrary.wordpress.com/2017/07/06/avrom-greenbaum-and-the-glasgow-jewish-institute-players-draft/ Avrom Greenbaum], who founded the [[Glasgow Jewish Institute Players]] (GJIP),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12590021.Forever_young_and_maternally_yours|title=Forever young and maternally yours|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref> and her brother, Leon Schuster, was production manager for GJIP, and, later, [[Glasgow Unity Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/portal/files/149374061/From_the_Gorbals_to_the_Lower_East_Side_the_theatrical_and_social_cosmopolitanism_of_the_Glasgow_Jewish_Institute_Players.pdf|title=Biography|website=pure.qub.ac.uk|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIda married doctor, Allan Berkeley, until his death in 1990, after 45 years of marriage. At the time of his death, she was appearing in ''The Steamie'' and had to leave the cast. The couple had two children, Howard and Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/evening-times/20060922/281951718302046|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=pressreader.com|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> She lived in Glasgow.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[La mort en direct]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[A Shot at Glory]]'' (2000)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0776843}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schuster, Ida}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish centenarians]]\n[[Category:Scottish Jews]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ida_Schuster"}
